    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[Er87b] Erd\\H{o}s, P., Some combinatorial and metric problems in geometry. Intuitive geometry (Si\\'{o}fok, 1985) (1987), 167-177.\n \n [Er90] Erd\\H{o}s, Paul, Some of my favourite unsolved problems. A tribute to Paul Erd\\H{o}s (1990), 467-478.\n \n [Ko24c] Z. Kov\\'{a}cs, A note on Erd\\H{o}s's mysterious remark. arXiv:2412.05190 (2024).",
      "remarks": "For $n=3$ the equilateral triangle is the only such set. For $n=4$ the square or two equilateral triangles sharing an edge give two non-similar examples.\n\nFor $n=5$ the regular pentagon is the unique such set (which has two distinct distances). Erd\\H{o}s mysteriously remarks in \\cite{Er90} this was proved by 'a colleague'. (In \\cite{Er87b} this is described as 'a colleague from Zagreb (unfortunately I do not have his letter)'.) A published proof of this fact is provided by Kov\\'{a}cs \\cite{Ko24c}.\n\nIn \\cite{Er87b} Erd\\H{o}s says that there are at least two non-similar examples for $6\\leq n\\leq 9$.\n\nThe minimal possible number of distinct distances is the subject of [89]."
    },
